  "prompt": "Why do people say a pregnancy is a nine months when it is actually 40 weeks?",
  "response": "People often refer to pregnancy as lasting nine months because it's a simpler and more relatable way to express the duration. However, the actual average length of a full-term pregnancy is about 40 weeks, or 280 days, measured from the first day of the last menstrual period.\n\nThe nine-month approximation comes from dividing 40 weeks by approximately 4.3 weeks per month (since some months have more days than others). This gives us a bit over 9 months (9.3 months, to be more precise). \n\nFor simplicity and ease of understanding, people generally round this down to nine months. However, healthcare providers typically use the 40-week measurement for more precise tracking and monitoring of the pregnancy.",
